{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:03:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:03:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13983"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13983"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.05,0.15,0.03,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55098"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40616"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"878"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2418"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13393"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55098"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of intermittent dysphagia. During an episode she experiences chest discomfort and a sensation of food getting stuck in her lower throat. These symptoms occur every few days and last no longer than one minute, with normal swallowing between episodes. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks 2-3 standards of alcohol daily. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A barium swallow is performed. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Distal oesophageal spasm","Eosinophilic oesophagitis","Achalasia","Oesophageal cancer","Oesophageal stricture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe barium swallow shows numerous simultaneous tertiary contractions in the mid and lower oesophagus. This, and the patient\u0027s symptoms of intermittent dysphagia and chest pain, are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Edistal (formerly diffuse) oesophageal spasm (DES)\u003C/strong\u003E. This is an idiopathic oesophageal motility disorder characterised by premature, uncoordinated and rapidly propagated contractions in the oesophagus. While barium swallow is not highly sensitive or specific for diagnosing DES, it may demonstrate a typical \u0027corkscrew\u0027 or \u0027rosary bead\u0027 appearance. High-resolution manometry is now the gold-standard for DES diagnosis, and would usually show spastic or premature contractions in the distal oesophagus with normal lower oesophageal sphincter relaxation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a failure of the lower oesophageal sphincter to relax, leading to progressive dysphagia for both solids and liquids. The barium swallow in achalasia typically shows a dilated oesophagus with a \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance at the gastro-oesophageal junction, which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with progressive dysphagia, often accompanied by weight loss and other systemic symptoms. The long duration of symptoms (one year) and the intermittent nature of the dysphagia make cancer less likely in this case. Additionally, a tumour would be visible as a filling defect on the barium swallow, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal stricture\u003C/strong\u003E would cause consistent rather than intermittent dysphagia, and would be visible as a narrowing on the barium swallow, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dysphagia, but it typically presents with more persistent symptoms and is often associated with a history of atopy or food allergies. The barium swallow in eosinophilic oesophagitis may show rings, strictures, or narrowing, but would not typically show the simultaneous contractions seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Distal oesophageal spasm is characterised by intermittent dysphagia due to premature, uncoordinated oesophageal contractions."],"references":["Khalaf, Mohamed, et al. Distal esophageal spasm: a review. The American Journal of Medicine 131.9 (2018): 1034-1040."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40616"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13983"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21083"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21083"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4AvJAkJBE1PBPojxO8ep8VxXn1237R.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4AvJAkJBE1PBPojxO8ep8VxXn1237R.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":356,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40616"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T17:24:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T17:24:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55098"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags"